FAQS = {
    'tire inflators': [('What PSI range matters for a home tire inflator?','Preset accuracy and usable airflow matter more than inflated max PSI claims. For normal cars and SUVs, an inflator that comfortably reaches 40 to 50 PSI with reasonable speed is enough.'),('Are cordless tire inflators good enough for trucks?','Some are, but not all. For truck tires, larger batteries, better heat control, and more airflow make a real difference.'),('How long can you run a tire inflator continuously?','Check the duty cycle. Many portable units need cooling breaks after several minutes, especially when inflating larger tires from low pressure.'),('Should I buy a 12V or battery tire inflator?','Buy 12V if you want sustained power and battery if you value convenience. Many drivers keep a cordless inflator for top-offs and a stronger corded unit for harder jobs.'),('Do portable tire inflators replace full shop compressors?','Not really. Portable inflators are for tire maintenance and emergencies, while shop compressors are better for air tools and faster repeated inflation.'),('How accurate are digital tire inflators?','Good ones are close enough for everyday use, but a separate gauge is still smart if you care about precision or you are airing up after off-road driving.')],
    'car wash kits': [('Do I need a foam cannon to wash my car safely?','No. A foam cannon is nice, but the safer factors are good wash technique, clean microfiber, and not grinding dirt back into the paint.'),('Are expensive car wash kits worth it?','Sometimes. Premium kits usually include better towels and stronger chemistry, but a solid mid-range kit is enough for most daily drivers.'),('What should a complete car wash kit include?','At minimum, look for wash soap, microfiber towels, wheel cleaning tools, drying support, and at least one paint-protection product.'),('Can one kit handle paint, wheels, and interior?','Some can, but specialist products usually perform better. The best all-around kits cover the basics while leaving room for targeted add-ons later.'),('How often should I replace microfiber towels?','Replace them when they get stiff, contaminated, or stop releasing dirt cleanly after washing. Towels matter more than many buyers realize.'),('Is a bucket wash still better than drive-through car washes?','Usually yes. A careful hand wash is gentler on paint and gives you more control over contact, chemicals, and drying.')],
    'espresso makers': [('Can a budget espresso maker make real espresso?','It can make a drink that is much closer to cafe espresso than pod machines, but consistency improves a lot once the grinder and temperature control get better.'),('Do I need a separate grinder for espresso?','Usually yes. A capable grinder matters as much as the machine because espresso is extremely sensitive to grind size and consistency.'),('What is the easiest type of espresso maker to live with?','Super-automatic machines are the easiest day to day, while semi-automatics offer better control and usually better long-term drink quality.'),('How much maintenance does an espresso machine need?','Regular rinsing, backflushing when supported, steam wand cleaning, and occasional descaling are part of ownership. Ignoring maintenance causes bad coffee fast.'),('Is Breville better than DeLonghi?','Not universally. Breville often wins on enthusiast-friendly workflow, while DeLonghi can be very strong for convenience and all-in-one appeal.'),('What is the best espresso machine for milk drinks?','Machines with reliable steam power and stable temperature control do best. Milk-drink households should weight steam performance heavily.')],
    'dutch ovens': [('What size Dutch oven is most versatile?','A 5.5 to 6.5 quart Dutch oven is the sweet spot for most households. It is large enough for braises and soups without becoming annoying to handle.'),('Is enamel better than bare cast iron?','For most home kitchens, yes. Enamel is easier to maintain and more forgiving with acidic foods, though bare cast iron still excels for camp cooking and high abuse.'),('Why are Le Creuset and Staub so expensive?','Their enamel quality, fit and finish, and long-term reputation are genuinely stronger than most budget options. Whether that matters to you depends on how often you use the pot.'),('Can a Dutch oven go from stove to oven?','Yes, that is one of the main reasons people buy one. Just confirm the lid knob and enamel are rated for the temperatures you plan to use.'),('Are Dutch ovens good for bread?','Very. Their heat retention and lid design make them excellent for trapping steam and building crust during sourdough baking.'),('How do you clean an enameled Dutch oven?','Warm water, gentle scrub tools, and patience work best. Avoid harsh thermal shock and overly aggressive metal tools that can damage enamel.')],
    'pasta makers': [('Is a manual pasta maker better than an electric one?','Manual machines usually offer better texture control and durability, while electric pasta makers are faster and easier for busy weeknight cooks.'),('What pasta maker is best for beginners?','A dependable manual roller like the Marcato Atlas 150 is still one of the best starting points because it teaches the process clearly.'),('Do electric pasta makers make the same pasta as roller machines?','Not exactly. Extruded pasta has a different texture and format than rolled sheet pasta, so the best choice depends on what you cook most.'),('How hard is cleanup?','Manual rollers are usually easier to maintain because you mainly brush off dried dough. Electric extrusion machines save labor during prep but can take more cleanup.'),('Can I make ravioli with any pasta maker?','Not efficiently. Ravioli is easiest when you have good sheet control plus either ravioli attachments or a simple manual cutting setup.'),('Are cheap pasta makers worth buying?','Some are fine for casual use, but the better-built machines track straighter, last longer, and feel less frustrating once you use them a few times.')],
    'sous vide machines': [('Is sous vide safe for home cooking?','Yes, when you follow proper temperature and timing guidance. Precision is a strength of sous vide, but food safety still depends on using the method correctly.'),('Do I need a vacuum sealer for sous vide?','Not necessarily. Many home cooks use quality zip bags and water displacement successfully, though vacuum sealers are better for frequent use and storage.'),('What wattage is enough for sous vide?','Around 800 to 1100 watts is enough for most home tasks. Bigger baths and faster heat-up benefit from more power, but app quality and clamp design also matter.'),('Is Joule better than Anova?','Joule often wins on compact design and app polish, while Anova has a broader install base and a familiar ecosystem. The better pick depends on your workflow.'),('What foods benefit most from sous vide?','Steak, chicken breast, pork chops, eggs, and meal-prep proteins benefit quickly because precise doneness is easy to repeat.'),('Do I still need to sear after sous vide?','Usually yes. Sous vide handles internal doneness, while a final sear adds the texture and flavor most people expect from finished meat.')],
    'instant pots': [('What size Instant Pot should most people buy?','Six quarts is still the most versatile choice for most households. It handles common recipes well without taking over the kitchen.'),('Is the Instant Pot Pro worth more than the Duo?','Often yes for frequent users. The Pro adds nicer controls, a better inner pot, and a more premium overall feel.'),('Can an Instant Pot replace a slow cooker?','Sometimes. It can slow cook, but dedicated slow cookers still feel more intuitive for some people and often have simpler long-cook ergonomics.'),('Are Instant Pots hard to learn?','Not really. The interface looks busier than it is, and most buyers are comfortable after a few simple recipes.'),('Do I need an air fryer combo model?','Only if you truly want the crisping function. Combo models are useful, but they are larger and not automatically the best choice for every kitchen.'),('What are the most useful Instant Pot accessories?','Extra sealing rings, a steamer basket, egg rack, and glass lid for non-pressure cooking are the accessories most owners actually keep using.')]
}

